all the great ioy and pleasure which they receiued to~ s&eacute;e the wonderfull meruayles of those two Knights was tourned into great sorrow and heauinesse, and b&eacute;egan amongst them grieuous lamentations, but especially the Qu&eacute;ene, who fell in a deadly sound, &amp; so remained more then one houre, but in the meane time this inuinsible <HI>Knight</HI> not making any stay at the death of the Gyaunt, without departing fro~ the king <HI>Lyseo,</HI> did such wonderfull d&eacute;edes round about him, that they durst oot come nigh him to assalt him by a great space, but with great sorrow withdrew themselues, b&eacute;ecause their liues depended in receiuing but one blow of his hands, if h&eacute;e chaunced to hit them right, and although a far off they threw at him Darts, Launces, and swoords, as well at his Horse as at him, yet they did him little harme, for that his armour was such as the historie hath shewed, and his horse was all couered with a very small and light mayle, made by such art, that ther was no weapon able to cut nor pearce it, for so the Prince <HI>Meridian</HI> had caused it to bee made, of whom h&eacute;e wonne his armour as you haue read, which dyd not a little profit in the mightie and immortal deeds of this inuinsible <HI>knight,</HI> for if that his owne armour and the ar|mour of his Horse had not b&eacute;ene of so great force and strength, it had not b&eacute;ene possible for him to haue fini|shed and brought to an ende so many perillous battayles and contentions as hee hath done. When this good knight saw that his enimies with great feare dyd flye from him and gaue him way, h&eacute;e went vnto the king <HI>Lyseo</HI> and tooke him in his armes, and rubbed and chafed him in such sort, that h&eacute;e came againe vnto himselfe, and when hee saw the great perill and daunger wherein h&eacute;e was brought, and the great slaughter which the <HI>knight</HI> of the <HI>Sunne</HI> hadde made&punc; h&eacute;e lift vp his hands to heauen, and