<DIV2 N="63" TYPE="chapter">
<HEAD>How the Prince Brandizel was deliuered from the tor|ment of the Sea, and what happened vnto him after|wards. Chapter. 63.</HEAD>
<P>_IN great peril to be drowned the prince <HI>Bran|dizel</HI> found himselfe in that furious torment, which chaunced vnto them at the Sea, but God would not permit that such a knight as h&eacute;e was should dye, but first to acknowledge his Christian lawe, dyd direct his fortune in such sort, that the planke wheron he swam, was carryed by those vniuersall and great rouling waues vnto the shoare, which s&eacute;emed to b&eacute;e very good, fresh, and fertiel. When this wearyed and afflicted Prince was a land, h&eacute;e knew the Countrie, for that h&eacute;e had b&eacute;ene in it b&eacute;efore, and it was the kingdome of <HI>Polonia,</HI> whereas h&eacute;e did deliuer and cleere out of the power of the Gyant, the fayre Princesse <HI>Clarinea,</HI> his Lady, and for that h&eacute;e knew the Countrie very well, one way h&eacute;e was very sad and sorrowfull, for the great perill in the which remained hir very friend <HI>Clauerindo,</HI> &amp; other|wise h&eacute;e was the gladdest man in all the world, for that h&eacute;e was in that Countrie, and so nigh vnto the Princesse his Lady, but when h&eacute;e considered with himselfe that h&eacute;e was on foot, and so euill intreated with the sea hee was ashamed so to shew himselfe b&eacute;efore the King, neyther knew h&eacute;e no<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="apex" EXTENT="1+ letters"> what to doo, nor whether hee might goe, for to remedie him selfe in that necessitie. The time of the y&eacute;ere as then was very hot, and after that h&eacute;e had dryed himselfe in the Sun, h&eacute;e put himselfe into a gallant fresh &amp; greene Forrest, which
<PB N="249" REF="258">
was along the sea side, &amp; comming vnto a fountaine of very cleere <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="apex" EXTENT="1 word"> christalline water, shadowed with boughs of verye greene <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="apex" EXTENT="1 word"> odoriferous tre<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="apex" EXTENT="1+ letters">s, he stooped and dronke of the same wate<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="apex" EXTENT="1+ letters">, &amp; after he had well refreshed hims<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="apex" EXTENT="1+ letters">lfe he sa<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="apex" EXTENT="1+ letters">e downe vpon <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="apex" EXTENT="1 word"> gr&eacute;ene grasse, &amp; pulled off his helme &amp; laid himselfe downe, &amp; what with the pittering of the leaues of the trees, <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="apex" EXTENT="1 word"> with the pleasant aire, likewise with the sw&eacute;et noise of the running of the water, he fell in a sound sleepe, &amp; being ther a <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="apex" EXTENT="1 word">, the king of <HI>Polonia</HI> who was on hunting in the same forrest, chanced with his <HI>knights,</HI> for to come vnto the same place, &amp; when the king &amp; his <HI>knights</HI> did first see him, they were greatly amazed to see a <HI>knight</HI> of so gentle dispo|sition to lie along vpon the grasse, &amp; especially in that place, but by reason his helme was off, they did very much behold him, &amp; in the end they knew him to be the prince <HI>Brandizel,</HI> <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="apex" EXTENT="1 word"> great fri<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="apex" EXTENT="1+ letters">nd, at the which he was greatly amazed for to see him ther alone, &amp; without any horse, yet was he the gladst man in all the world, &amp; did alight from his horse &amp; went vn|to him, and shaking him by the armes, the prince did awake out of his sleepe, &amp; when he knew the king he was much a|mazed, &amp; with a trise hee arose vp and went for to kisse his hands, but the king who did loue him very well did embrace him with g<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="apex" EXTENT="1+ letters">eat loue, and asked him how he came into that country all alone, &amp; by what aduenture. To whom y^e prince said, with great desire to serue your <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="apex" EXTENT="1 word">, &amp; there he de|clare<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="apex" EXTENT="1+ letters"> vn<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="apex" EXTENT="1+ letters">o him all that hapned vnto him, &amp; vnto the prince <HI>Clauerindo,</HI> &amp; vnderstanding all, the king was very sorow|full for the great perill and danger in the which the prince <HI>Clauerindo</HI> remained, although he thought all for the best, &amp; was very glad to see in that country the prince <HI>Brandizel,</HI> for that he had a great d<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="apex" EXTENT="1+ letters">sire to ma<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="apex" EXTENT="1+ letters">ie him vnto the princes <HI>Clarinea</HI> his daughter&punc; for that it s&eacute;emed vnto him to be one of the be<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="apex" EXTENT="1+ letters">t <HI>knights</HI> in all the world.</P>
